00:02:50.690 --> 00:02:55.620
So we are asked in this problem
to circle the support vectors.

00:02:55.620 --> 00:02:59.020
Draw the edges of the street
and then the dotted line

00:02:59.020 --> 00:03:00.850
in the middle that
separates them,

00:03:00.850 --> 00:03:05.940
the separator, as a dashed line.

00:03:05.940 --> 00:03:11.140
And then to give w and b.

00:03:11.140 --> 00:03:14.920
So what are w and b?

00:03:14.920 --> 00:03:21.300
Well, there's a few
important equations in SVMs

00:03:21.300 --> 00:03:22.924
that we really
hope-- and I'm going

00:03:22.924 --> 00:03:25.340
to tell you we're lucky in
this because we don't have to--

00:03:25.340 --> 00:03:26.910
but we really hope
that we don't have

00:03:26.910 --> 00:03:30.960
to use because they provide
a huge number of variables.

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:33.500
So one of those
crucial equations

00:03:33.500 --> 00:03:43.190
is that for a plus support
vector, w vector dot x plus,

00:03:43.190 --> 00:03:48.095
the plus support
vector, plus b equals 1.

00:03:50.885 --> 00:03:55.630
w dot x minus plus
b equals minus 1.

00:03:55.630 --> 00:04:00.490
And w dot that dotted
line-- I don't know,

00:04:00.490 --> 00:04:06.140
we'll call it dot dot
dot-- plus b equals 0.

00:04:06.140 --> 00:04:07.410
So what does this mean?

00:04:07.410 --> 00:04:09.400
There are a lot of vectors.

00:04:09.400 --> 00:04:12.430
Well, I mean, we're usually
in two-dimensional space,

00:04:12.430 --> 00:04:14.810
so we can basically
just say that there's

00:04:14.810 --> 00:04:17.899
two components of this
w vector, w1 and w2.

00:04:17.899 --> 00:04:20.130
And they're just
two coefficients

00:04:20.130 --> 00:04:21.810
in a linear equation.

00:04:21.810 --> 00:04:25.850
So for instance, what we're
interested in finding,

00:04:25.850 --> 00:04:27.690
this dot dot dot
line, we'll just

00:04:27.690 --> 00:04:29.920
call that x, so
with nothing on it.

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:31.840
Actually, maybe
that'll be easier.

00:04:31.840 --> 00:04:44.900
This is equivalent to saying
w1x1 plus w2x2 plus b equals 0,

00:04:44.900 --> 00:04:49.380
where x1 is this,
and x2 is this.

00:04:49.380 --> 00:04:52.210
We would possibly
call them x and y.

00:04:52.210 --> 00:04:55.690
So one way to think
about it is w1,

00:04:55.690 --> 00:05:03.200
we'll call it a, ax
plus-- call w2 b-- by.

00:05:03.200 --> 00:05:05.890
Oh, don't call it b.

00:05:05.890 --> 00:05:12.340
Well, ax plus cy plus b
equals-- I'll put this all in

00:05:12.340 --> 00:05:15.740
parentheses-- this is basically
an equation like this.

00:05:15.740 --> 00:05:29.830
Or y equals negative a
over c x minus b over c.

00:05:29.830 --> 00:05:33.270
It's basically y
equals mx plus b.

00:05:33.270 --> 00:05:34.394
Does everyone see that?

00:05:34.394 --> 00:05:35.810
This thing that
we're looking for,

00:05:35.810 --> 00:05:39.490
this w dot x plus b
equals 0, is the equation

00:05:39.490 --> 00:05:43.440
of a line in
Cartesian coordinates.

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:45.840
It just looks uglier.

00:05:45.840 --> 00:05:50.320
Normally, when we're doing
all this solving for w and b,

00:05:50.320 --> 00:05:54.790
we would have to put
in tons of equations,

00:05:54.790 --> 00:05:57.940
plug in all of the
support vectors in there.

00:05:57.940 --> 00:06:03.220
And we'd have to use these
little devils called alphas.

00:06:03.220 --> 00:06:06.280
Alphas essentially--
if it wasn't clear

00:06:06.280 --> 00:06:08.650
in the lecture, which it
usually isn't completely

00:06:08.650 --> 00:06:12.420
clear to everyone, wasn't clear
to me completely-- alphas,

00:06:12.420 --> 00:06:14.120
the way I like to
think about them,

00:06:14.120 --> 00:06:16.630
the alphas in this
problem is they

00:06:16.630 --> 00:06:20.390
are the weight of how
significant any particular

00:06:20.390 --> 00:06:25.280
point on the graph is towards
creating the boundary.

00:06:25.280 --> 00:06:28.845
The higher the
alpha is, the more

00:06:28.845 --> 00:06:32.210
that that point narrows
in the boundary.

00:06:32.210 --> 00:06:34.740
The lower the alpha is, the
less that that point narrows

00:06:34.740 --> 00:06:38.570
in the boundary, the
wider the road can be.

00:06:38.570 --> 00:06:40.320
And if that point
doesn't do anything,

00:06:40.320 --> 00:06:42.327
if that point is irrelevant
and could be removed

00:06:42.327 --> 00:06:44.410
and it wouldn't affect the
boundary, the alpha is?

00:06:44.410 --> 00:06:45.230
Everyone?

00:06:45.230 --> 00:06:45.964
AUDIENCE: Zero.

00:06:45.964 --> 00:06:46.630
PROFESSOR: Zero.

00:06:46.630 --> 00:06:49.940
Well, that was one person, but
you can suffice for everyone.

00:06:49.940 --> 00:06:51.060
The alpha is 0.

00:06:51.060 --> 00:06:53.620
And that means if it's not a
support vector, if it's not

00:06:53.620 --> 00:06:56.520
one of the vectors on
the boundary lines,

00:06:56.520 --> 00:07:02.210
it will always have an alpha
of 0 because it doesn't affect.

00:07:02.210 --> 00:07:06.380
So keeping that in
mind, there's a few fun

00:07:06.380 --> 00:07:08.072
and important
equations about alphas

00:07:08.072 --> 00:07:10.030
that we'll need if we're
solving many equations

00:07:10.030 --> 00:07:13.990
for many unknowns, which
hopefully we won't have to do.

00:07:13.990 --> 00:07:18.380
The sum over the
positive alphas equals

00:07:18.380 --> 00:07:23.300
the sum over the alphas--
the negative points.

00:07:23.300 --> 00:07:25.530
And this is true
over all the points.

00:07:25.530 --> 00:07:28.830
But since all of
the alphas are 0,

00:07:28.830 --> 00:07:30.560
except for the support
vectors, it also

00:07:30.560 --> 00:07:32.710
means the alphas of
the positive support

00:07:32.710 --> 00:07:35.250
vectors are equal to the
alphas of the negative support

00:07:35.250 --> 00:07:36.490
vectors.

00:07:36.490 --> 00:07:41.070
Additionally, our old
buddy, the w vector,

00:07:41.070 --> 00:07:46.450
is equal to the
sum over all i that

00:07:46.450 --> 00:07:56.800
are plus vectors of wi
alpha i minus m over j

00:07:56.800 --> 00:08:01.500
minus vectors of wj alpha j.

00:08:04.060 --> 00:08:07.510
Now, all of these equations
can be used in a bloody mess

00:08:07.510 --> 00:08:11.110
to figure out the answer to
what we're trying to find,

00:08:11.110 --> 00:08:13.940
which is circles--
well, actually, they

00:08:13.940 --> 00:08:15.580
can't be used as
circle support vectors

00:08:15.580 --> 00:08:17.820
and draw the dotted line.

00:08:17.820 --> 00:08:20.450
But once we do that,
all these equations

00:08:20.450 --> 00:08:23.860
can be used in a bloody mess to
give us the next thing that we

00:08:23.860 --> 00:08:25.380
want, which is w and b.

00:08:30.390 --> 00:08:35.120
So fortunately, there's
another way to get w and b.

00:08:35.120 --> 00:08:38.429
If you guys really want,
at the end of the hour

00:08:38.429 --> 00:08:43.080
we can also try to
derive w and b using

00:08:43.080 --> 00:08:44.740
the many equations
in many unknowns,

00:08:44.740 --> 00:08:46.200
but it's a bit painful.

00:08:46.200 --> 00:08:47.930
We'll try to do it the cool way.

00:08:47.930 --> 00:08:50.545
So let's start off.

00:08:50.545 --> 00:08:51.920
This is the one
we're looking at.

00:08:51.920 --> 00:08:54.590
We need to find where
the support vectors are.

00:08:54.590 --> 00:08:59.010
So the first thing we need
to do is simply eye it.

00:08:59.010 --> 00:09:00.970
Fortunately, on the
test, there will always

00:09:00.970 --> 00:09:02.960
be ones that you can
eye if you're supposed

00:09:02.960 --> 00:09:04.850
to circle the support vectors.

00:09:04.850 --> 00:09:08.200
There's obviously
some number of pluses

00:09:08.200 --> 00:09:09.460
and some number of minuses.

00:09:09.460 --> 00:09:11.564
I say obviously, but maybe not.

00:09:11.564 --> 00:09:12.980
But hopefully
obviously, and we'll

00:09:12.980 --> 00:09:15.490
find out because I'm going
to call on random people.

00:09:15.490 --> 00:09:19.899
So give me a positive
support vector.

00:09:19.899 --> 00:09:28.120
AUDIENCE: Um, going to the one
that looked like [INAUDIBLE]?

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:31.210
PROFESSOR: Which plus
sign, [INAUDIBLE]?

00:09:31.210 --> 00:09:32.580
AUDIENCE: One on the right.

00:09:32.580 --> 00:09:33.380
PROFESSOR: The one all
the way on the right.

00:09:33.380 --> 00:09:35.840
Yeah, that plus sign is a
positive support vector.

00:09:35.840 --> 00:09:37.170
That's good.

00:09:37.170 --> 00:09:37.920
All right?

00:09:37.920 --> 00:09:39.256
Excellent.

00:09:39.256 --> 00:09:40.880
Now, give me a negative
support vector.

00:09:44.810 --> 00:09:45.310
That one?

00:09:49.360 --> 00:09:50.114
No?

00:09:50.114 --> 00:09:51.030
AUDIENCE: Yeah, sorry.

00:09:51.030 --> 00:09:52.113
PROFESSOR: Ah, no problem.

00:09:52.113 --> 00:09:53.530
Give me a negative
support vector.

00:09:53.530 --> 00:09:54.904
AUDIENCE: I should
definitely ask

00:09:54.904 --> 00:09:56.470
you, what's a support vector?

00:09:56.470 --> 00:09:57.955
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:57.955 --> 00:09:59.440
PROFESSOR: That is
a good question.

00:09:59.440 --> 00:10:03.720
The question is, what
is a support vector?

00:10:03.720 --> 00:10:08.600
How many other people will
admit to having this question?

00:10:08.600 --> 00:10:09.100
See?

00:10:09.100 --> 00:10:12.225
You're not alone.

00:10:12.225 --> 00:10:12.725
OK.

00:10:15.510 --> 00:10:18.390
Before I go on, I'm going
to assume-- you guys make

00:10:18.390 --> 00:10:22.331
sure I'm correct-- Monday
was, just being sure

00:10:22.331 --> 00:10:23.580
so I can tailor based on this.

00:10:23.580 --> 00:10:27.230
Monday was the support
vector machine lecture.

00:10:27.230 --> 00:10:30.470
But it was also very
difficult to follow.

00:10:30.470 --> 00:10:32.460
That's what I usually expect.

00:10:32.460 --> 00:10:35.170
So what is a support vector?

00:10:35.170 --> 00:10:40.350
Well, all these pluses and
minuses, if we were me,

00:10:40.350 --> 00:10:43.600
and if, I guess--
yeah, if we were me

00:10:43.600 --> 00:10:47.490
and if I was describing this
problem, the one that we work

00:10:47.490 --> 00:10:49.970
out in class, I would
call them points

00:10:49.970 --> 00:10:51.840
because they're on the graph.

00:10:51.840 --> 00:10:53.320
They're points.

00:10:53.320 --> 00:10:55.515
They're data points.

00:10:55.515 --> 00:10:59.240
But however, in more difficult
versions of this problem

00:10:59.240 --> 00:11:01.760
that have n
dimensions, where n is

00:11:01.760 --> 00:11:03.330
some ridiculous
number of dimensions

00:11:03.330 --> 00:11:05.040
that you're never
going to graph.

00:11:05.040 --> 00:11:08.310
Like say some of the
research I'm doing now,

00:11:08.310 --> 00:11:10.060
I could use support
vector machines

00:11:10.060 --> 00:11:15.420
on some of these articles that
I'm reading about cyber events

00:11:15.420 --> 00:11:17.520
to try to figure out
if there's a real event

00:11:17.520 --> 00:11:19.780
or if it's just someone
complaining about how we're

00:11:19.780 --> 00:11:21.540
really vulnerable or
something like that

00:11:21.540 --> 00:11:23.550
and no event actually happened.

00:11:23.550 --> 00:11:25.820
So the reason why they
call these guys vectors is

00:11:25.820 --> 00:11:28.990
when you're not able to graph
them on a Cartesian plane,

00:11:28.990 --> 00:11:33.790
there's still this long vector
of many different dimensions.

00:11:33.790 --> 00:11:37.750
Right now, though, these
points represent the vectors.

00:11:37.750 --> 00:11:39.134
This is very simple.

00:11:39.134 --> 00:11:40.550
It's easier to
view them this way.

00:11:40.550 --> 00:11:44.685
But for instance, that
plus at negative 1, 2

00:11:44.685 --> 00:11:46.060
represents the
fact that there is

00:11:46.060 --> 00:11:49.670
a vector going in the
direction of negative 1, 2

00:11:49.670 --> 00:11:55.415
with a magnitude such that
it reaches negative 1, 2.

00:11:55.415 --> 00:11:57.540
So all these points are
just a point representation

00:11:57.540 --> 00:11:58.180
of a vector.

00:11:58.180 --> 00:12:01.400
You probably, in any class
that worked with vectors,

00:12:01.400 --> 00:12:04.330
saw this, saw vectors being
represented as points.

00:12:04.330 --> 00:12:04.830
Question?

00:12:05.593 --> 00:12:07.865
AUDIENCE: Always from the
respect to the origin?

00:12:07.865 --> 00:12:08.490
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:12:08.490 --> 00:12:10.680
The question is always
with respect to the origin.

00:12:10.680 --> 00:12:12.842
The answer is
canonically, when vectors

00:12:12.842 --> 00:12:15.340
are represented as
points, yes, it's always

00:12:15.340 --> 00:12:17.820
with respect to the origin.

00:12:17.820 --> 00:12:21.604
So that's the basic idea is that
all these points are vectors.

00:12:21.604 --> 00:12:22.770
So what are support vectors?

00:12:22.770 --> 00:12:25.400
Well, you could call them
support points for this case.

00:12:25.400 --> 00:12:27.191
But the reason we call
them support vectors

00:12:27.191 --> 00:12:28.800
is again, in the
generalized case

00:12:28.800 --> 00:12:31.980
that you might be doing in
the real world with real AI,

00:12:31.980 --> 00:12:33.480
you're going to
have a giant vector.

00:12:33.480 --> 00:12:36.560
And it's not just going
to be points on a graph.

00:12:36.560 --> 00:12:37.850
Well, usually.

00:12:37.850 --> 00:12:41.970
So the support vectors,
the support points,

00:12:41.970 --> 00:12:44.000
we found one of them correctly.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:45.660
It's this guy.

00:12:45.660 --> 00:12:50.124
They're going to be the
ones that again, they

00:12:50.124 --> 00:12:51.290
don't have an alpha of zero.

00:12:51.290 --> 00:12:54.740
They're the ones that bind
in the, as Petra calls it,

00:12:54.740 --> 00:12:57.780
the road, the boundary lines.

00:12:57.780 --> 00:12:59.930
They're going to be
on the edge of plus.

00:12:59.930 --> 00:13:02.010
Whichever direction
we draw it, this plus

00:13:02.010 --> 00:13:04.616
is the edge of the plus region.

00:13:04.616 --> 00:13:06.947
If we made this the
edge of the plus region

00:13:06.947 --> 00:13:09.030
and everything on this
side is plus and everything

00:13:09.030 --> 00:13:10.710
on this side is
minus, we'd be screwed

00:13:10.710 --> 00:13:15.170
because there's two pluses
on the other side of that.

00:13:15.170 --> 00:13:18.040
Generally, when trying
to find a support vector,

00:13:18.040 --> 00:13:22.100
you do something a little bit
similar to my crazy method

00:13:22.100 --> 00:13:24.950
of doing nearest
neighbors, and try

00:13:24.950 --> 00:13:30.860
to find a plus-minus pair
that's close to each other.

00:13:30.860 --> 00:13:33.650
Sometimes though, it's
not just two points

00:13:33.650 --> 00:13:35.900
because sometimes if you try
to draw the simple-minded

00:13:35.900 --> 00:13:38.760
thing, which is
the perpendicular

00:13:38.760 --> 00:13:41.780
bisector of the two points,
you get screwed because there's

00:13:41.780 --> 00:13:43.800
another point in your way.

00:13:43.800 --> 00:13:46.400
So now that I've
given away a clue,

00:13:46.400 --> 00:13:48.722
let's go-- and hopefully
that made sense to you guys.

00:13:48.722 --> 00:13:50.805
The support vectors are
the ones on the edges that

00:13:50.805 --> 00:13:53.320
are just barely a plus
for sure, or just barely

00:13:53.320 --> 00:13:54.390
a minus for sure.

00:13:54.390 --> 00:13:55.040
Let's go back.

00:13:55.040 --> 00:13:56.900
Can you give me a
negative support vector?

