if you can see it.

00:29:52.770 --> 00:29:54.850
We've added in yet
some new points.

00:29:54.850 --> 00:29:58.100
We've got this point up here
and this point down there.

00:29:58.100 --> 00:30:00.640
So I think pretty clearly
this plus and minus

00:30:00.640 --> 00:30:01.906
are the closest to each other.

00:30:01.906 --> 00:30:03.780
But what happens if we
take the perpendicular

00:30:03.780 --> 00:30:09.200
bisector between these
two and do like this?

00:30:09.200 --> 00:30:12.194
This plus is in the middle.

00:30:12.194 --> 00:30:13.860
So therefore, this
plus is going to have

00:30:13.860 --> 00:30:15.540
to also be a support vector.

00:30:15.540 --> 00:30:20.090
So we can't just draw this line.

00:30:20.090 --> 00:30:21.810
We have to include this.

00:30:21.810 --> 00:30:23.040
What's our best division?

00:30:25.660 --> 00:30:27.800
Vertical lines, that's right.

00:30:27.800 --> 00:30:34.252
Vertical lines just so.

00:30:34.252 --> 00:30:39.100
And that means that the
equation of our boundary,

00:30:39.100 --> 00:30:42.085
the dotted line here, y-axis.

00:30:46.180 --> 00:30:49.695
So the equation of the boundary
with the y-axis, then b

00:30:49.695 --> 00:30:50.770
equals 0.

00:30:50.770 --> 00:30:53.490
And hell, w2 equals 0.

00:30:53.490 --> 00:30:55.860
So the only thing that is not--

00:30:55.860 --> 00:30:58.770
AUDIENCE: Wait, w1 [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:58.770 --> 00:31:00.077
PROFESSOR: w2 equals 0.

00:31:04.460 --> 00:31:06.560
So w2 equals 0.

00:31:06.560 --> 00:31:07.490
b equals 0.

00:31:07.490 --> 00:31:12.420
But w1 is not equal to
zero because it's just

00:31:12.420 --> 00:31:15.070
the equation of the y-axis.

00:31:15.070 --> 00:31:21.270
So we therefore know
that the equation is just

00:31:21.270 --> 00:31:25.980
w1 times x equals 0.

00:31:32.420 --> 00:31:35.400
So it's w1 times x equals 0.

00:31:35.400 --> 00:31:38.470
And we know that that
just means essentially

00:31:38.470 --> 00:31:39.777
that x is going to be some k.

00:31:39.777 --> 00:31:41.860
It's also going to be
negative because of the fact

00:31:41.860 --> 00:31:44.400
that the pluses are
still on the left.

00:31:44.400 --> 00:31:47.610
Then we're going to have to
figure out what that k is.

00:31:47.610 --> 00:31:51.500
We'll use our old trick-- by
this point old, hopefully.

00:31:51.500 --> 00:31:54.060
One over magnitude
of w equals d.

00:31:54.060 --> 00:31:55.280
This time d is just 1.

00:31:58.650 --> 00:32:02.050
So therefore, magnitude
of w equals 1.

00:32:02.050 --> 00:32:04.450
There's only one component in w.

00:32:04.450 --> 00:32:07.000
So therefore w1 is

00:32:07.000 --> 00:32:08.360
AUDIENCE: -1.

00:32:08.360 --> 00:32:12.330
PROFESSOR: -1 because
the plus is on the left.

00:32:12.330 --> 00:32:13.900
Do people see that?

00:32:13.900 --> 00:32:14.810
Not too bad.

00:32:14.810 --> 00:32:16.563
This one's easy to
calculate the w.

00:32:16.563 --> 00:32:20.460
But it's not as easy
to get all the alphas.

00:32:20.460 --> 00:32:23.740
But let's move on to
a new and even more

00:32:23.740 --> 00:32:30.920
fun-- maybe not-- question,
which is this guy.

00:32:30.920 --> 00:32:34.100
As you can see-- well maybe not.

00:32:34.100 --> 00:32:36.960
This is a one
dimensional vector.

00:32:36.960 --> 00:32:38.970
These vectors only have
a single dimension.

00:32:38.970 --> 00:32:41.380
So it just looks like
a number line here.

00:32:41.380 --> 00:32:46.610
That dimension varies from it
looks like -9 to positive 9.

00:32:46.610 --> 00:32:48.247
It just has one component.

00:32:48.247 --> 00:32:50.705
You don't have to worry about
any of these crazy magnitudes

00:32:50.705 --> 00:32:53.530
with two components,
just everything

00:32:53.530 --> 00:32:55.100
as a single component.

00:32:55.100 --> 00:32:59.300
However, it's obvious
that a linear basis

00:32:59.300 --> 00:33:01.890
line is going to completely
screw us up here,

00:33:01.890 --> 00:33:05.090
since lines at this point
are just like, grunk,

00:33:05.090 --> 00:33:06.024
all these are pluses.

00:33:06.024 --> 00:33:06.940
All these are minuses.

00:33:06.940 --> 00:33:08.860
Well, great, that
doesn't get them all.

00:33:08.860 --> 00:33:10.570
So how are we going to do it?

00:33:10.570 --> 00:33:13.180
Well, we're going to use what
is usually perhaps the hardest

00:33:13.180 --> 00:33:15.180
thing in SVMs, but
in this case is not

00:33:15.180 --> 00:33:17.010
going to be too bad for us.

00:33:17.010 --> 00:33:19.520
We're going to use a kernel.

00:33:19.520 --> 00:33:23.160
Now, based on how little
I understood kernels

00:33:23.160 --> 00:33:26.320
the first time I
took this class,

00:33:26.320 --> 00:33:27.970
I'm guessing that
you guys would like

00:33:27.970 --> 00:33:30.714
to have some explanation
on these kernels.

00:33:30.714 --> 00:33:31.630
You probably saw them.

00:33:31.630 --> 00:33:35.070
You remember the kernels from
Patrick's lecture vaguely?

00:33:35.070 --> 00:33:36.120
There's this phi.

00:33:36.120 --> 00:33:37.160
And then there's this k.

00:33:37.160 --> 00:33:39.730
And then they get
really complicated.

00:33:39.730 --> 00:33:43.420
OK, so here's how
the kernel works.

00:33:43.420 --> 00:33:45.660
The basic idea is this.

00:33:45.660 --> 00:33:51.420
And I'll write it over here.

00:33:51.420 --> 00:33:53.030
Oh, wow, there's more stuff.

00:33:53.030 --> 00:33:53.739
OK.

00:33:53.739 --> 00:33:54.780
I'll write it right here.

00:33:54.780 --> 00:33:56.730
The basic idea is this.

00:33:56.730 --> 00:34:01.910
We're taking the normal space,
which is this number line

00:34:01.910 --> 00:34:04.100
or it could be any
kind of normal space,

00:34:04.100 --> 00:34:06.100
and we're going
to take a vector,

00:34:06.100 --> 00:34:11.230
we're going to put into
it a function called phi.

00:34:11.230 --> 00:34:16.120
And phi of vector x brings
x into some new dimension.

00:34:16.120 --> 00:34:18.659
Phi, or "phee" if
you like it better,

00:34:18.659 --> 00:34:21.400
is usually a nasty piece
of work and something

00:34:21.400 --> 00:34:22.929
you never, ever want to look at.

00:34:22.929 --> 00:34:24.820
Sometimes it's not too bad.

00:34:24.820 --> 00:34:27.679
Phi is the function that brings
it into the new dimension.

00:34:27.679 --> 00:34:29.224
OK?

00:34:29.224 --> 00:34:31.570
And when you brought the
data into a new dimension,

00:34:31.570 --> 00:34:34.070
sometimes you can just cut a
straight line in that dimension

00:34:34.070 --> 00:34:36.699
and you'll just be happy.

00:34:36.699 --> 00:34:42.159
However, something
that was noted

00:34:42.159 --> 00:34:48.449
by the very, very smart inventor
of support vector machines

00:34:48.449 --> 00:34:54.710
is that you don't actually
need to work with function phi,

00:34:54.710 --> 00:34:58.740
even if phi is an absolutely
horrible monstrosity, because

00:34:58.740 --> 00:35:04.850
of the fact that you never need
to know what all these vectors

00:35:04.850 --> 00:35:10.400
x actually are in the new
space, at least not directly.

00:35:10.400 --> 00:35:11.930
In none of these
equations up here

00:35:11.930 --> 00:35:14.720
do we ever use x by itself.

00:35:14.720 --> 00:35:19.440
However, we do use x being dot
product with something else.

00:35:19.440 --> 00:35:23.780
So he figured out a very
sneaky and excellent shortcut.

00:35:26.580 --> 00:35:29.510
OK, so-- oh, I
shouldn't use x1 and x2.

00:35:29.510 --> 00:35:35.530
I'll use x and z.

00:35:35.530 --> 00:35:37.910
So if you have two
vectors, x and z, which

00:35:37.910 --> 00:35:40.140
are in a regular
space, you put them

00:35:40.140 --> 00:35:42.650
into this function
called the kernel.

00:35:42.650 --> 00:35:55.120
Then it will tell you
phi x dotted with phi z.

00:35:55.120 --> 00:35:59.920
And if you have that,
you don't need phi.

00:35:59.920 --> 00:36:00.934
Does everyone see that?

00:36:00.934 --> 00:36:02.600
Does everyone see why
we don't need phi?

00:36:02.600 --> 00:36:04.099
Look at all these
equations up here.

00:36:04.099 --> 00:36:07.770
We have never looked
at x by itself

00:36:07.770 --> 00:36:12.390
in these vector
equations at least.

00:36:12.390 --> 00:36:15.610
Now, calculating alphas, yeah,
that gets a little bit fuzzy.

00:36:18.650 --> 00:36:21.240
Also, you may ask,
why would you do this?

00:36:21.240 --> 00:36:22.720
You can't calculate the alphas.

00:36:22.720 --> 00:36:29.200
It turns out that actually,
other than for these very

00:36:29.200 --> 00:36:31.800
simple linear problems,
human minds cannot calculate

00:36:31.800 --> 00:36:32.740
the alphas.

00:36:32.740 --> 00:36:35.827
In fact, you run
a very complicated

00:36:35.827 --> 00:36:36.785
quadratic optimization.

00:36:36.785 --> 00:36:39.090
In fact, finding
out the best alphas

00:36:39.090 --> 00:36:42.720
is the thing that you
hill climb on when you're

00:36:42.720 --> 00:36:44.440
doing SVMs in the real world.

00:36:44.440 --> 00:36:47.075
You say, all right,
I'll run my algorithm

00:36:47.075 --> 00:36:48.770
when I know there's
only one peak, which

00:36:48.770 --> 00:36:51.430
is very, very good because
it's quadratic optimization.

00:36:51.430 --> 00:36:53.080
Let me figure out the alphas.

00:36:53.080 --> 00:36:55.010
So in fact, it doesn't
matter that you

00:36:55.010 --> 00:37:00.359
can't use these alpha equations
to figure out the alphas if you

00:37:00.359 --> 00:37:01.900
only know the kernel
function and not

00:37:01.900 --> 00:37:05.280
the phi function because
normally, the computer

00:37:05.280 --> 00:37:09.166
figures out the alphas for you
with quadratic optimization.

00:37:09.166 --> 00:37:10.540
Just in these
simple problems, we

00:37:10.540 --> 00:37:12.400
know you can
calculate the alphas.

00:37:12.400 --> 00:37:17.120
So we have the kernel,
which basically gives us

00:37:17.120 --> 00:37:19.500
the dot product of the
things in the new space.

00:37:19.500 --> 00:37:22.200
So being that as it may, I'll
give you the kernel here.

00:37:22.200 --> 00:37:23.410
I'd like you give me phi.

00:37:26.670 --> 00:37:29.670
Someone got an idea, whose
name was Susan Q. Random

00:37:29.670 --> 00:37:31.360
Student, apparently.

00:37:31.360 --> 00:37:37.980
She got an idea that if we had
a kernel for x and z-- actually,

00:37:37.980 --> 00:37:39.210
they're not vectors, I guess.

00:37:39.210 --> 00:37:43.430
There just single components.

00:37:43.430 --> 00:37:55.500
And the kernel equals cosine Pi
over 4x times cosine Pi over 4

00:37:55.500 --> 00:38:07.260
z plus sine Pi over 4x
plus sine Pi over 4z.

00:38:10.630 --> 00:38:13.670
So that is the new dot product.

00:38:16.180 --> 00:38:17.090
Oh, wait, sorry.

00:38:17.090 --> 00:38:21.030
I put one of the z's not
inside the parentheses.

00:38:21.030 --> 00:38:22.340
That was silly of me.

00:38:22.340 --> 00:38:28.220
So cosine of the
quantity pi Over 4x times

00:38:28.220 --> 00:38:31.300
cosine of the quantity Pi over
4z plus sine of quantity Pi

00:38:31.300 --> 00:38:36.480
over 4x plus sine of quantity
Pi over 4z is the new product.

00:38:36.480 --> 00:38:37.910
So that begs the question.

00:38:37.910 --> 00:38:42.150
This is an easy one so
we can calculate the phi.

00:38:42.150 --> 00:38:47.620
What is phi of x?

00:38:47.620 --> 00:38:51.025
We're actually taking
it from one dimension

00:38:51.025 --> 00:38:53.890
and we may be playing around
with it a lot to get this.

00:38:53.890 --> 00:38:56.910
And this thing has
become a new dot product.

00:38:56.910 --> 00:38:58.532
It replaces dot product.

00:38:58.532 --> 00:39:00.240
And remember, the dot
product for scalars

00:39:00.240 --> 00:39:02.750
would have just been multiplying
two numbers together.

00:39:02.750 --> 00:39:05.000
So it actually makes it a
little bit more complicated.

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:07.650
Does anyone think
they know the phi?

00:39:07.650 --> 00:39:08.930
Oh, we got one.

00:39:08.930 --> 00:39:09.896
What do you think?

00:39:09.896 --> 00:39:10.888
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:39:13.870 --> 00:39:16.228
