00:47:01.594 --> 00:47:04.029
AUDIENCE: So what's the
intuition behind the w?

00:47:04.029 --> 00:47:06.451
We solved it and figured
out numbers and integrations

00:47:06.451 --> 00:47:06.951
with it.

00:47:06.951 --> 00:47:08.671
But what is it in relation to--

00:47:08.671 --> 00:47:10.420
PROFESSOR: Question
is, what is intuition?

00:47:10.420 --> 00:47:12.976
What is w?

00:47:12.976 --> 00:47:14.980
W Is the dividing line.

00:47:14.980 --> 00:47:16.996
It is the drop
dead dividing line.

00:47:16.996 --> 00:47:18.620
When I say the drop
dead dividing line,

00:47:18.620 --> 00:47:21.960
you like those big, bold
solid lines over there.

00:47:21.960 --> 00:47:23.680
Those are your
pretty certain lines.

00:47:23.680 --> 00:47:25.057
Everything past
that was a minus.

00:47:25.057 --> 00:47:26.640
In your training,
it's that everything

00:47:26.640 --> 00:47:30.150
past the big bold line there was
a plus in your training stuff.

00:47:30.150 --> 00:47:32.290
But the dotted line is
the one you're really

00:47:32.290 --> 00:47:34.350
going to use in the test data.

00:47:34.350 --> 00:47:36.770
In the test data, when
push comes to shove,

00:47:36.770 --> 00:47:39.910
you might get something if
it's inside of that gutter.

00:47:39.910 --> 00:47:41.879
And if it's on the,
say, of that one

00:47:41.879 --> 00:47:44.420
up there, if it's on the upper
left side of that dotted line,

00:47:44.420 --> 00:47:47.040
you're going to call it a plus.

00:47:47.040 --> 00:47:49.870
So that dotted line is
your decision boundary.

00:47:49.870 --> 00:47:54.010
And that is basically the idea.

00:47:54.010 --> 00:47:56.952
And in fact, the way that
the algorithm would do it

00:47:56.952 --> 00:47:58.660
on the computer is it
would quadratically

00:47:58.660 --> 00:48:01.430
optimize the alphas,
which messes around

00:48:01.430 --> 00:48:02.610
with the dotted line.

00:48:02.610 --> 00:48:06.230
And by quadratically
maximizing the alphas-- you see

00:48:06.230 --> 00:48:07.884
how the alphas add up to a w.

00:48:07.884 --> 00:48:08.925
It just checks it around.

00:48:08.925 --> 00:48:12.519
And eventually, it finds, oh,
making the alpha of this one 0

00:48:12.519 --> 00:48:13.810
makes it a better optimization.

00:48:13.810 --> 00:48:15.980
You're trying to get the
widest possible road.

00:48:15.980 --> 00:48:17.715
It would eventually
come out to this.

00:48:17.715 --> 00:48:19.340
This is trivial for
a human to eyeball.

00:48:19.340 --> 00:48:21.500
But some real
problems with 200 data

00:48:21.500 --> 00:48:24.720
points that have to get one or
two of them wrong, classified,

00:48:24.720 --> 00:48:27.960
and you may be using a
quadratic kernel or something

00:48:27.960 --> 00:48:29.500
that, you can't do that.

00:48:29.500 --> 00:48:30.510
You just can't.

00:48:30.510 --> 00:48:32.930
Well, maybe can,
in which case you

00:48:32.930 --> 00:48:34.782
should be getting a
MacArthur Fellowship

00:48:34.782 --> 00:48:35.740
or something like that.

00:48:35.740 --> 00:48:38.310
But the computer can.

00:48:38.310 --> 00:48:40.680
And the basic idea is
when it comes down to it,

00:48:40.680 --> 00:48:44.860
it figures out the alphas, that
the best w for the widest road.

00:48:44.860 --> 00:48:47.410
And the w s your
decision boundary.

